    }
  </style>

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />

  <div class="dcf-wrapper">
    <h1>Johnson Controls (JCI) Intrinsic Value</h1>
    <div class="subtitle">
      <span>A Two-Stage Discounted Cash Flow Analysis</span>
      <span class="badge">Compiled by Gemini 3.1</span>
      <span>Updated March 2026</span>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ VERDICT CARD ═══ -->
    <div class="verdict-card">
      <div class="verdict-header">Calculated Intrinsic Value</div>
      <div class="iv-number">${intrinsicValuePerShare.toFixed(2)}</div>
      <div class="current-price">
        Current Market Price: {currentPrice !== null ? `$${currentPrice.toFixed(2)}` : 'N/A'}
      </div>

      {currentPrice !== null && (
        <div class={`verdict-pill ${isUndervalued ? 'undervalued' : marginOfSafety < 0 ? 'overvalued' : 'fair'}`}>
          {verdictStr} ({marginOfSafety > 0 ? '+' : ''}{(marginOfSafety * 100).toFixed(1)}% Margin of Safety)
        </div>
      )}
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
    <h2>Methodology</h2>
    <p>This analysis uses a <strong>Two-Stage Discounted Cash Flow (DCF)</strong> model. A DCF model estimates the intrinsic value of an investment based on its expected future cash flows. The premise is that the value of a company today is the sum of all the free cash flow it will generate in the future, discounted back to today's present value.</p>

    <div class="methodology-box">
      <p><strong>Why two-stage?</strong> We project explicit cash flows for the next 10 years (Stage 1 & 2), assuming higher growth initially as JCI capitalizes on commercial building efficiency trends and data center cooling, followed by a deceleration. Then, we calculate a Terminal Value (Stage 3) representing cash flows into perpetuity at a mature, stable growth rate.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
    <h2>Core Assumptions & Rationale</h2>
    <p>The output of any DCF is entirely dependent on the inputs. Here are the exact numbers we used and the logic behind them.</p>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="row-label">Metric</th>
            <th>Input</th>
            <th>Rationale</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Base Year FCF</td>
            <td>${baseFcf}M</td>
            <td>Latest trailing 12-month Free Cash Flow. JCI's cash generation can be lumpy due to working capital and recent restructuring (divesting non-core HVAC/ADT assets).</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Discount Rate (WACC)</td>
            <td>{(discountRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            <td>Derived via CAPM. 10-Year Treasury yield is {(treasury10Y * 100).toFixed(2)}%. We use an Equity Risk Premium of {(erp * 100).toFixed(1)}% and a Beta of {beta}, reflecting cyclical industrial exposure.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Phase 1 Growth (Years 1-5)</td>
            <td>{(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            <td>Driven by secular tailwinds in data center cooling (OpenBlue solutions), energy efficiency retrofits, and smart building upgrades. Margin expansion from recent divestitures supports FCF conversion.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Phase 2 Growth (Years 6-10)</td>
            <td>{(growthRatePhase2 * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            <td>Growth decelerates as initial retrofit cycles peak and the business scales down to structural economic growth levels.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Terminal Growth Rate</td>
            <td>{(terminalGrowthRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
            <td>Long-term sustainable growth into perpetuity, roughly matching historical global GDP growth and inflation.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Shares Outstanding</td>
            <td>{currentShares}M</td>
            <td>Current diluted shares. Does not explicitly model future buybacks, making the per-share value slightly conservative if JCI aggressively repurchases stock.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Net Debt</td>
            <td>${(currentDebt - currentCash)}M</td>
            <td>Total Debt of ${currentDebt}M minus Cash & Equivalents of ${currentCash}M. Subtracted from Enterprise Value.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS ═══ -->
    <h2>10-Year Cash Flow Projections</h2>
    <p>Applying our growth rates to the base Free Cash Flow, here is the projected cash generation over the next decade.</p>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="row-label">Year</th>
            <th>Projected FCF ($M)</th>
            <th>Growth Rate</th>
            <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {projectedFcf.map((item, index) => (
            <tr>
              <td class="row-label">Year {item.year}</td>
              <td>${item.value.toFixed(0)}</td>
              <td>{(item.growth * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
              <td>${pvFcf[index].toFixed(0)}</td>
            </tr>
          ))}
          <tr style="background: rgba(74, 143, 231, 0.1);">
            <td class="row-label highlight-cell">Sum of PV (1-10)</td>
            <td></td>
            <td></td>
            <td class="highlight-cell">${fcfTotalPv.toFixed(0)}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
    <h2>Terminal & Enterprise Value</h2>
    <p>The Terminal Value accounts for all cash flows generated from Year 11 onwards into perpetuity. We use the Gordon Growth Model for this calculation.</p>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Year 10 FCF</td>
            <td>${finalYearFcf.toFixed(0)}M</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Terminal Growth Rate</td>
            <td>{(terminalGrowthRate * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Calculated Terminal Value</td>
            <td>${terminalValue.toFixed(0)}M</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label highlight-cell">PV of Terminal Value</td>
            <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toFixed(0)}M</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>Finally, we sum the present value of explicit cash flows and the terminal value to find the Enterprise Value. We then bridge to Equity Value by adding cash and subtracting debt.</p>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">PV of Cash Flows (Years 1-10)</td>
            <td>${fcfTotalPv.toFixed(0)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">PV of Terminal Value</td>
            <td>${pvTerminalValue.toFixed(0)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-top: 2px solid #1e293b;">
            <td class="row-label"><strong>Enterprise Value</strong></td>
            <td><strong>${enterpriseValue.toFixed(0)}</strong></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Plus: Cash & Equivalents</td>
            <td>${currentCash}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Less: Total Debt</td>
            <td>${currentDebt}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-top: 2px solid #1e293b;">
            <td class="row-label highlight-cell">Total Equity Value</td>
            <td class="highlight-cell">${equityValue.toFixed(0)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="row-label">Divided by Shares Outstanding</td>
            <td>{currentShares}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="background: rgba(74, 143, 231, 0.1);">
            <td class="row-label highlight-cell">Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
            <td class="highlight-cell">${intrinsicValuePerShare.toFixed(2)}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY MATRIX ═══ -->
    <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
    <p>Valuation is imprecise. A small change in assumptions can drastically alter the final intrinsic value. This 5x5 matrix shows how the per-share value changes based on varying the Discount Rate and the Phase 1 Growth Rate.</p>

    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table class="sensitivity-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th class="row-label">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
            {sensitivityGrowthRates.map(g => (
              <th class={Math.abs(g - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001 ? 'current' : ''}>
                {(g * 100).toFixed(1)}%
              </th>
            ))}
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {sensitivityGrid.map(row => (
            <tr>
              <td class="row-label">{(row.dr * 100).toFixed(1)}%</td>
              {row.values.map((val, i) => (
                <td class={(Math.abs(row.dr - discountRate) < 0.001) && (Math.abs(sensitivityGrowthRates[i] - growthRatePhase1) < 0.001) ? 'current' : ''}>
                  ${val.toFixed(2)}
                </td>
              ))}
            </tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p>The highlighted cell represents our base-case assumptions.</p>

    <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
    <h2>Model Risks & Limitations</h2>
    <p>What this DCF inherently misses or assumes:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Cyclicality:</strong> Commercial construction and building upgrades are economically sensitive. A severe recession would sharply impair FCF generation, rendering our {(growthRatePhase1 * 100).toFixed(1)}% growth assumption far too optimistic.</li>
      <li><strong>Margin Execution:</strong> JCI is divesting lower-margin residential assets to become a "pure-play" commercial building solutions provider. The model assumes they successfully execute this pivot and expand FCF margins. If restructuring drags on, FCF will miss targets.</li>
      <li><strong>Data Center Concentration:</strong> A large part of the bullish thesis relies on cooling solutions for AI data centers. If data center build-outs cool off or if competitors (e.g., Trane, Carrier) take more market share, growth will suffer.</li>
      <li><strong>Debt Load:</strong> With ${currentDebt}M in debt, JCI carries significant leverage. In a higher-for-longer interest rate environment, refinancing this debt will eat into free cash flow.</li>
    </ul>

