    <div class="faq">
      <details>
        <summary>Why use a Two-Stage DCF instead of a single stage?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          Companies rarely grow at a constant rate forever. JCI has near-term catalysts (data centers, divestitures, energy efficiency mandates) that justify higher growth ({(growthRatePhase1*100).toFixed(1)}%) in the short term. However, it's a large, mature industrial company, so growth will eventually mean-revert down toward GDP levels. A two-stage model captures this trajectory better than a single flat rate.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How did you arrive at the {(discountRate*100).toFixed(1)}% discount rate?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          We used the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM). We start with a risk-free rate of {(treasury10Y*100).toFixed(2)}% (the 10-Year US Treasury yield). We add an Equity Risk Premium of {(erp*100).toFixed(1)}%, multiplied by JCI's Beta of {beta}. This reflects the required return investors should demand for taking on the specific volatility and risk profile of JCI's stock.
        </div>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why is Free Cash Flow better than Net Income for valuation?</summary>
        <div class="faq-answer">
          Net Income includes non-cash expenses (like depreciation) and ignores necessary capital expenditures (CapEx) to maintain and grow the business. Free Cash Flow measures the actual cash left over that can be distributed to shareholders via dividends or buybacks. In valuation, cash is king.
        </div>
      </details>
